{"source_key":"sha256-6a126603c159e5957000b366b122ff4e","record_index":1232,"record_hash":"sha256:2681589c0c1da03e026bd695978e4f80ce69ea5ede72c9d8bb2367237a4347eb","timestamp":"2026-05-20T17:59:28.300Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"**Findings**\\n\\n- [crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:399): `max_turns = Some(0)` still reads and validates the transcript before slicing to an empty turn set. That makes an empty window fail on missing/corrupt transcript, which is surprising API behavior. Slice first; return early if empty.\\n\\n- [crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:408): windowed reads hydrate a full `HashMap<String, Value>` for every transcript record, so `Some(1)` can fail because of an unrelated old malformed transcript entry and pays full transcript parse cost. Better: slice turns, read selected details, collect needed hashes, then hydrate only those records.\\n\\n- [crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:113): public `TimelineTurn` stringifies fields that are already domain enums on write (`CaptureKind`, `SnapshotStatus`). That leaks storage looseness into the Rust API and accepts impossible values silently. Use typed public enums or a typed DTO conversion that validates stored strings.\\n\\n- [crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:517): `timeline_records` is really `hydrate_turn_records`, and merging it with the transcript lookup flow would fix the clone/full-map issue above. Current `.cloned()` is acceptable for owned API output, but it’s a symptom of the less direct hydration shape.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"times